## Verdict
PARTIAL

## Boundary integration
- [x] Pure substrate
- [x] Per-backend semaphore correct
- [ ] Per-task timeout via deadline-wait
- [x] Result order matches input

## New findings (if any)
[HIGH] src/polaris_graph/audit_ir/parallel_fetch.py:393 — `parallel_fetch` marks a future `TIMEOUT`, but it still exits through the `ThreadPoolExecutor` context manager, which waits for running workers to finish. In a direct probe, a `0.5s` fetch with `per_task_timeout=0.05` returned in about `0.505s`, so boundary 3 does not currently bound caller latency.

[MEDIUM] src/polaris_graph/audit_ir/parallel_fetch.py:398 — all per-task deadlines are anchored to one shared `submit_now`. Under worker or semaphore contention, a task can be recorded as `TIMEOUT` before it ever enters `fetcher.fetch`, which is not called out in the threat model.

[MEDIUM] src/polaris_graph/audit_ir/parallel_fetch.py:470 — `FetcherProtocolError` is not reliably surfaced promptly once other tasks are already running; the same executor shutdown behavior delays propagation until in-flight work completes.

[LOW] tests/polaris_graph/test_md8_phase1_parallel_fetch.py:217 — the cross-backend wall-clock assertion is flaky on this host. One full-suite run failed at `0.1229s` against the `< 0.12s` cutoff, then the suite passed on rerun.

## Final word
PARTIAL until the timeout path stops blocking on executor shutdown. Focused pytest ended `29 passed` on rerun, but the manual timeout probe shows the main timeout boundary is still functionally incomplete.
